# TigerBeetle's Factory & Init Patterns for `extern struct`

TigerBeetle uses **four distinct patterns** for constructing `extern struct` instances. Here they are from simplest to most complex:

---

## Pattern 1: Struct Literal with Default Field Values (the dominant pattern)

The most pervasive pattern. Fields that must be zero/empty are given inline defaults using `= 0`, `= @splat(0)`, or `= undefined`. There is no separate factory function — callers construct instances using Zig's struct literal syntax, specifying only the fields that differ from defaults.

**[`src/tigerbeetle.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/tigerbeetle.zig#L70-L83)**:
```zig
pub const AccountBalance = extern struct {
    debits_pending: u128,
    debits_posted: u128,
    credits_pending: u128,
    credits_posted: u128,
    timestamp: u64,
    reserved: [56]u8 = @splat(0),  // ← default: caller never has to set this

    comptime {
        assert(stdx.no_padding(AccountBalance));
        assert(@sizeOf(AccountBalance) == 128);
        assert(@alignOf(AccountBalance) == 16);
    }
};
```

**[`src/vsr/message_header.zig` — `Header.Ping`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/vsr/message_header.zig#L374-L432)**:
```zig
pub const Ping = extern struct {
    checksum: u128 = 0,           // ← defaults allow omitting in literal
    checksum_padding: u128 = 0,
    checksum_body: u128 = 0,
    checksum_body_padding: u128 = 0,
    nonce_reserved: u128 = 0,
    cluster: u128,                // ← no default: must be provided
    size: u32,
    ...
    reserved: [80]u8 = @splat(0),
    ...
};
```
The caller constructs this via `Ping{ .cluster = x, .size = y, ... }` — omitting all the `= 0` fields.

**The comptime block is non-negotiable** — every `extern struct` carries one to assert no accidental padding:
```zig
comptime {
    assert(stdx.no_padding(Account));
    assert(@sizeOf(Account) == 128);
    assert(@alignOf(Account) == 16);
}
```
`stdx.no_padding` is a comptime utility in [`src/stdx/stdx.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/stdx.zig) that walks all struct fields recursively and asserts `@bitSizeOf(T) == 8 * @sizeOf(T)`.

---

## Pattern 2: Named Factory Function Returning the Struct

Used when construction requires logic beyond field assignment — parsing, validation, byte-level reinterpretation. The function is a `pub fn` on the `extern struct` itself that returns `Self` by value.

### `Release.from()` — byte-reinterpretation factory
**[`src/multiversion.zig` L192–194](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/multiversion.zig#L173-L267)**:
```zig
pub const Release = extern struct {
    value: u32,

    comptime {
        assert(@sizeOf(Release) == 4);
        assert(@sizeOf(Release) == @sizeOf(ReleaseTriple));
        assert(stdx.no_padding(Release));
    }

    // Compile-time constant instances:
    pub const zero    = Release.from(.{ .major = 0, .minor = 0, .patch = 0 });
    pub const minimum = Release.from(.{ .major = 0, .minor = 0, .patch = 1 });

    // Factory function: reinterpret a ReleaseTriple's bytes as a Release.
    pub fn from(release_triple: ReleaseTriple) Release {
        return std.mem.bytesAsValue(Release, std.mem.asBytes(&release_triple)).*;
    }

    pub fn parse(string: []const u8) !Release {
        return Release.from(try ReleaseTriple.parse(string));
    }
};

pub const ReleaseTriple = extern struct {
    patch: u8,
    minor: u8,
    major: u16,

    comptime {
        assert(@sizeOf(ReleaseTriple) == 4);
        assert(stdx.no_padding(ReleaseTriple));
    }

    pub fn parse(string: []const u8) error{InvalidRelease}!ReleaseTriple {
        var parts = std.mem.splitScalar(u8, string, '.');
        const major = parts.first();
        const minor = parts.next() orelse return error.InvalidRelease;
        const patch = parts.next() orelse return error.InvalidRelease;
        if (parts.next() != null) return error.InvalidRelease;
        return .{        // ← plain struct literal
            .major = std.fmt.parseUnsigned(u16, major, 10) catch return error.InvalidRelease,
            .minor = std.fmt.parseUnsigned(u8, minor, 10) catch return error.InvalidRelease,
            .patch = std.fmt.parseUnsigned(u8, patch, 10) catch return error.InvalidRelease,
        };
    }
};
```

Key points:
- `Release.from()` uses `std.mem.bytesAsValue(...).* ` to safely reinterpret bytes — a common idiom when two `extern struct`s are guaranteed to have the same size/layout.
- Compile-time constant instances (`zero`, `minimum`) are declared as `pub const` fields on the struct itself, computed by calling the factory at comptime.

---

### `VSRState.root()` — named static factory with options struct
**[`src/vsr/superblock.zig` L156–200](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/vsr/superblock.zig#L110-L200)**:
```zig
pub const VSRState = extern struct {
    checkpoint: CheckpointState,
    replica_id: u128,
    members: vsr.Members,
    commit_max: u64,
    sync_op_min: u64,
    sync_op_max: u64,
    sync_view: u32 = 0,
    log_view: u32,
    view: u32,
    replica_count: u8,
    reserved: [779]u8 = @splat(0),

    comptime {
        assert(@sizeOf(VSRState) == 2048);
        assert(stdx.no_padding(VSRState));
    }

    // Named factory: takes an "options struct" (anonymous, non-extern) and returns VSRState
    pub fn root(options: struct {
        cluster: u128,
        replica_id: u128,
        members: vsr.Members,
        replica_count: u8,
        release: vsr.Release,
        view: u32,
    }) VSRState {
        return .{
            .checkpoint = .{
                .header = vsr.Header.Prepare.root(options.cluster),
                .parent_checkpoint_id = 0,
                .grandparent_checkpoint_id = 0,
                .free_set_blocks_acquired_checksum = comptime vsr.checksum(&.{}),
                // ... many more fields with explicit zero/computed values
                .storage_size = data_file_size_min,
                .release = options.release,
            },
            .replica_id = options.replica_id,
            .members = options.members,
            .replica_count = options.replica_count,
            .commit_max = 0,
            .sync_op_min = 0,
            .sync_op_max = 0,
            .log_view = 0,
            .view = options.view,
        };
    }
};
```
The anonymous `options: struct { ... }` parameter is a regular (non-extern) struct — this is a clean separation: the `extern struct` is for ABI; the options struct is just for ergonomic call sites.

---

## Pattern 3: `init()` Populating a Caller-Allocated `extern struct` (out-pointer pattern)

Used when the `extern struct` must cross an FFI boundary and its memory is caller-owned. The function signature takes `*ExternStruct` as an out-pointer rather than returning by value.

### `ClientInterface.init()` — FFI-safe out-pointer factory
**[`src/clients/c/tb_client/context.zig` L70–78](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/clients/c/tb_client/context.zig#L41-L136)**:
```zig
pub const ClientInterface = extern struct {
    // An extern union to ensure pointer fields are u64-sized on both 32- and 64-bit targets:
    context: extern union {
        ptr: ?*anyopaque,
        int_ptr: u64,
    },
    vtable: extern union {
        ptr: *const VTable,
        int_ptr: u64,
    },
    locker: Locker,   // also an extern struct
    reserved: u32,
    magic_number: u64,

    comptime {
        assert(@sizeOf(ClientInterface) == 32);
        assert(@alignOf(ClientInterface) == 8);
    }

    // Out-pointer init: caller allocates the extern struct, we populate it
    pub fn init(interface: *ClientInterface, context: *anyopaque, vtable: *const VTable) void {
        interface.* = .{             // ← assign via pointer dereference
            .context = .{ .ptr = context },
            .vtable = .{ .ptr = vtable },
            .locker = .{},
            .reserved = 0,
            .magic_number = 0,       // set to beetle sentinel AFTER all sub-init succeeds
        };
    }
};
```

The **magic number sentinel** is critical — it is written **last**, after all other initialization succeeds, so partial-init is detectable:

**[`src/clients/c/tb_client/context.zig` L401–404](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/clients/c/tb_client/context.zig#L367-L405)**:
```zig
// At the end of Context.init(), only after everything else succeeds:
client_out.magic_number = ClientInterface.beetle;  // 0xBEE71E
```

And all methods validate it before use:
```zig
pub fn submit(interface: *ClientInterface, packet: *Packet.Extern) Error!void {
    if (interface.magic_number != beetle) return Error.ClientInvalid;
    ...
}
```

### `tb_client_t` — the C-facing opaque wrapper
**[`src/clients/c/tb_client_exports.zig` L11–23](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/clients/c/tb_client_exports.zig#L11-L23)**:
```zig
pub const tb_client_t = extern struct {
    @"opaque": [4]u64,   // ← sized to hold a ClientInterface, opaque to C callers

    pub inline fn cast(self: *tb_client_t) *tb.ClientInterface {
        return @ptrCast(self);
    }

    comptime {
        // The comptime block guarantees layout compatibility:
        assert(@sizeOf(tb_client_t) == @sizeOf(tb.ClientInterface));
        assert(@bitSizeOf(tb_client_t) == @bitSizeOf(tb.ClientInterface));
        assert(@alignOf(tb_client_t) == @alignOf(tb.ClientInterface));
    }
};
```

The exported `init` function takes the out-pointer:
```zig
pub fn init(
    tb_client_out: *tb_client_t,     // ← out-pointer: caller allocates
    cluster_id_ptr: *const [16]u8,
    addresses_ptr: [*:0]const u8,
    addresses_len: u32,
    completion_ctx: usize,
    completion_callback: tb_completion_t,
) callconv(.c) tb_init_status {
    ...
    tb.init(
        std.heap.c_allocator,
        tb_client_out.cast(),     // reinterpret extern wrapper as real type
        cluster_id,
        addresses,
        ...
    ) catch |err| return init_error_to_status(err);
    return .success;
}
```

---

## Pattern 4: Comptime-Generic Factory (type-erased `extern struct` from generic types)

Used in the LSM tree to construct `extern struct` types at comptime via generic functions.

### `CompositeKeyType()` — returns an anonymous `extern struct`
**[`src/lsm/composite_key.zig` L13–93](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/lsm/composite_key.zig#L13-L93)**:
```zig
pub fn CompositeKeyType(comptime Field: type) type {
    // ...
    return extern struct {
        const CompositeKey = @This();

        field: Field align(field_bitsize_alignment),
        timestamp: u64,
        padding: Pad = 0,

        comptime {
            assert(@sizeOf(CompositeKey) == @sizeOf(Key));
            assert(stdx.no_padding(CompositeKey));
        }

        // Factory method on the returned type:
        pub inline fn tombstone_from_key(key: Key) CompositeKey {
            const timestamp: u64 = @truncate(key);
            assert(timestamp & tombstone_bit == 0);
            return .{                           // ← struct literal returned by value
                .field = key_prefix(key),
                .timestamp = timestamp | tombstone_bit,
                // padding defaults to 0
            };
        }
    };
}
```

The `IdTreeValue` in [`src/lsm/groove.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/lsm/groove.zig#L52-L79) follows the same tombstone factory pattern:
```zig
const IdTreeValue = extern struct {
    id: u128,
    timestamp: u64,
    padding: u64 = 0,

    comptime {
        assert(@sizeOf(IdTreeValue) == 32);
        assert(stdx.no_padding(IdTreeValue));
    }

    inline fn tombstone_from_key(id: u128) IdTreeValue {
        return .{
            .id = id,
            .timestamp = tombstone_bit,   // padding defaults to 0
        };
    }
};
```

And in [`src/lsm/groove.zig` L42–48](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/lsm/groove.zig#L42-L49) — `std.mem.zeroes()` to zero-initialize before patching a field:
```zig
inline fn tombstone_from_key(timestamp: u64) Object {
    assert(timestamp & tombstone_bit == 0);
    var value = std.mem.zeroes(Object);     // ← full zero-init
    value.timestamp = timestamp | tombstone_bit;
    return value;
}
```

---

## Summary of Patterns

| Pattern | When used | Signature shape |
|---|---|---|
| **Struct literal w/ field defaults** | Simple data structs (`Account`, `Transfer`, `Ping`) | No factory, caller uses `Type{ .x = y }` |
| **Named `from()`/`root()` factory returning `Self`** | Needs computation/parsing (`Release.from`, `VSRState.root`) | `pub fn from(input: T) ExternStruct` |
| **Out-pointer `init(*Self, ...)` → `void`** | FFI/C boundary, caller-owned memory (`ClientInterface.init`) | `pub fn init(self: *ExternStruct, ...) void` |
| **Comptime generic returning `extern struct`** | LSM internals, type-specialized storage types | `pub fn TypeFactory(comptime P: type) type { return extern struct { ... }; }` |

### Invariants TigerBeetle enforces on every `extern struct`

1. **`comptime { assert(stdx.no_padding(T)); }`** — never leave implicit uninitialized bytes
2. **`comptime { assert(@sizeOf(T) == N); }`** — size is fixed and known
3. **Reserved/padding fields default to `0` or `@splat(0)`** — the struct is always fully initialized
4. **When two `extern struct`s must be layout-compatible** (e.g. `tb_client_t` vs `ClientInterface`), a `comptime` block asserts `@sizeOf`, `@bitSizeOf`, and `@alignOf` all match
5. **Magic number sentinels** are written **last** in `init()`, enabling detection of uninitialized usage

