---

### Pattern 2: `comptime assert` for compile-time-knowable invariants

When the invalid condition can be detected at compile time, TigerBeetle uses `comptime assert`. This produces a **compile error** instead of a runtime panic, which is even better.

**[`src/stdx/stdx.zig` — `div_ceil`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/stdx.zig#L51-L70):**

```zig
pub inline fn div_ceil(numerator: anytype, denominator: anytype) @TypeOf(numerator, denominator) {
    comptime {
        switch (@typeInfo(@TypeOf(numerator))) {
            .int => |int| assert(int.signedness == .unsigned),
            .comptime_int => assert(numerator >= 0),
            else => @compileError("div_ceil: invalid numerator type"),
        }
        // ...
    }
    assert(denominator > 0);  // runtime check for runtime values
    // ...
}
```

**[`src/stdx/prng.zig` — type-level checks](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/prng.zig#L218):**

```zig
pub fn int_inclusive(prng: *PRNG, Int: anytype, max: Int) Int {
    comptime assert(@typeInfo(Int).int.signedness == .unsigned);
    // ...
}
```

**[`src/stdx/ring_buffer.zig` — buffer-type specialization](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/ring_buffer.zig#L40-L52):**

```zig
fn init_array() RingBuffer {
    comptime assert(buffer_type == .array);
    return .{ .buffer = undefined };
}

fn init_slice(allocator: mem.Allocator, capacity: usize) !RingBuffer {
    comptime assert(buffer_type == .slice);
    assert(capacity > 0);  // runtime: caller's responsibility
    // ...
}
```

---

### Pattern 3: `unreachable` for exhausted switch arms and post-loop invariants

`unreachable` is used in two narrow situations: after exhaustive `switch` arms that the type system can't prove exhaustive, and at the end of a loop that mathematically must have returned.

**[`src/stdx/prng.zig` — `enum_weighted_impl`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/prng.zig#L480-L494):**

```zig
fn enum_weighted_impl(prng: *PRNG, Enum: type, weights: anytype) Enum {
    // ...
    assert(total > 0);
    var pick = prng.int_inclusive(u64, total - 1);
    inline for (fields) |field| {
        const weight = @field(weights, field.name);
        if (pick < weight) return @as(Enum, @enumFromInt(field.value));
        pick -= weight;
    }
    unreachable; // mathematically impossible to reach here
}
```

**[`src/stdx/ring_buffer.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/ring_buffer.zig#L100-L112):**

```zig
pub fn get(self: *const RingBuffer, index: usize) ?T {
    if (self.buffer.len == 0) unreachable; // zero-capacity is a programming error
    // ...
}
```

---

### Pattern 4: `@panic` for truly exceptional runtime conditions (not parameter validation)

`@panic` is reserved for situations that are not parameter errors but rather environmental failures or things that must be visible even in ReleaseFast (where `assert` is stripped). It is **not used for parameter validation**:

```zig
// src/time.zig — hardware/kernel regression, not a parameter error
if (m < self.monotonic_guard) @panic("a hardware/kernel bug regressed the monotonic clock");

// src/io/linux.zig — environmental failure
@panic("another process holds the data file lock");

// src/aof.zig — unrecoverable I/O failure  
_ = completion;
_ = result catch @panic("aof fsync failure");
```

---

### Pattern 5: Errors for user-facing / recoverable input, not programming errors

The clear dividing line is: if the invalid value comes from **user input** (CLI flags, parsed data), it's returned as an error with a diagnostic message. If it comes from **a programmer calling the API wrong**, it's `assert`.

**[`src/stdx/prng.zig` — `Ratio.parse_flag_value` (user input → error)](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/prng.zig#L53-L81):**

```zig
pub fn parse_flag_value(
    string: []const u8,
    static_diagnostic: *?[]const u8,
) error{InvalidFlagValue}!Ratio {
    // ...
    if (denominator == 0) {
        static_diagnostic.* = "denominator is zero:";
        return error.InvalidFlagValue;  // user error
    }
    if (numerator > denominator) {
        static_diagnostic.* = "ratio greater than 1:";
        return error.InvalidFlagValue;  // user error
    }
    return ratio(numerator, denominator);  // calls assert internally for programmer use
}
```

---

### Summary table

| Situation | Tool |
|---|---|
| Programmer passed an invalid argument | `assert(condition)` — panics in Debug/ReleaseSafe |
| Condition knowable at compile time | `comptime assert(condition)` — compile error |
| Branch logically impossible to reach | `unreachable` |
| Environmental failure (HW, OS, lock) | `@panic("message")` |
| User-provided input is invalid | `return error.SomeError` |
| Not-yet-implemented code path | `stdx.unimplemented("reason")` |

---

