### Pattern 3: `unreachable` for exhausted switch arms and post-loop invariants

`unreachable` is used in two narrow situations: after exhaustive `switch` arms that the type system can't prove exhaustive, and at the end of a loop that mathematically must have returned.

**[`src/stdx/prng.zig` — `enum_weighted_impl`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/prng.zig#L480-L494):**

```zig
fn enum_weighted_impl(prng: *PRNG, Enum: type, weights: anytype) Enum {
    // ...
    assert(total > 0);
    var pick = prng.int_inclusive(u64, total - 1);
    inline for (fields) |field| {
        const weight = @field(weights, field.name);
        if (pick < weight) return @as(Enum, @enumFromInt(field.value));
        pick -= weight;
    }
    unreachable; // mathematically impossible to reach here
}
```

**[`src/stdx/ring_buffer.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/ring_buffer.zig#L100-L112):**

```zig
pub fn get(self: *const RingBuffer, index: usize) ?T {
    if (self.buffer.len == 0) unreachable; // zero-capacity is a programming error
    // ...
}
```

